<P>
This page outlines my previous research.
<P>
<HR>


<p> 
<B><I>Themes</I></B>.  
My research covers a broad range of many-particle phenomena and
issues, with particular focus on unconventional states and new
theoretical tools.  The two main themes are:

<ul>

<li> many-particle physics in ultra-cold trapped atomic gases;  

<li> applying techniques from <I>quantum information theory</I> (such as
entanglement measures) to study condensed matter phenomena.

</ul>



<P>
<B><I>Trapped atom gases</I></B>.
About half of my past work involved laser-cooled trapped atomic gases, which
provide the opportunity to explore quantum many-particle phenomena in a novel,
highly tunable, setting.  I worked on non-equilibrium phenomena 
[<A
 HREF="TrackRecord_feb08.html#self_sweep_PRA05">1</A>,<A
 HREF="TrackRecord_feb08.html#self_vortex-antivortex_unpubl">2</A>], on `polarized'
fermionic atom gases [<A
 HREF="TrackRecord_feb08.html#self_polarized_PRA06">3</A>,<A
 HREF="TrackRecord_feb08.html#self_Rice_PRL06">4</A>,<A
 HREF="TrackRecord_feb08.html#self_deformation_PRL07">5</A>], and on vortices in Bose
condensates [<A
 HREF="TrackRecord_feb08.html#self_superstring_PRL05">6</A>,<A
 HREF="TrackRecord_feb08.html#self_vortex-antivortex_unpubl">2</A>].  My
most significant contributions addressed the pairing of trapped polarized
fermions and non-equilibrium phenomena, described further below.

<P>
<B><I>Polarized fermions</I></B>.
Unequal occupation of the two spin states (``polarization'') of pairing
fermions leads to new subtle effects and a rich phase diagram.
My early analysis of the first experiments resulted in a highly cited paper,
now a basic reference for the large theoretical community studying polarized
fermionic atoms
[<A
 HREF="TrackRecord_feb08.html#self_polarized_PRA06">3</A>].
We also collaborated directly with the experimental group at Rice university
[<A
 HREF="TrackRecord_feb08.html#self_Rice_PRL06">4</A>].
Our latest calculations [<A
 HREF="TrackRecord_feb08.html#self_deformation_PRL07">5</A>] have been central to
ongoing efforts to understand differences seen between two experiments (at
Rice and MIT).  The main theme in Refs.&nbsp;[<A
 HREF="TrackRecord_feb08.html#self_polarized_PRA06">3</A>,<A
 HREF="TrackRecord_feb08.html#self_Rice_PRL06">4</A>,<A
 HREF="TrackRecord_feb08.html#self_deformation_PRL07">5</A>] is  <I>phase separation</I> and other
effects due to the external trap. 

<P>
<B><I>Non-equilibrium phenomena</I></B>.
In Ref.&nbsp;[<A
 HREF="TrackRecord_feb08.html#self_sweep_PRA05">1</A>],
I studied dissociation dynamics of molecules as the magnetic field is ramped
across a Feshbach resonance to the side where they are not stable.
In Ref.&nbsp;[<A
 HREF="TrackRecord_feb08.html#self_vortex-antivortex_unpubl">2</A>], I explored the dynamics
of a <I>vortex dipole</I> in a trapped condensate. 
These are examples of new classes of non-equilibrium dynamics studies
made possible by cold atoms, namely, the detailed study of time
evolution: (a) after and during sweeps faster than system dynamics
timescales, as in [<A
 HREF="TrackRecord_feb08.html#self_sweep_PRA05">1</A>]; (b) after engineering
non-equilibrium quantum states, as in
[<A
 HREF="TrackRecord_feb08.html#self_vortex-antivortex_unpubl">2</A>]. 
<BR>The work of Ref.&nbsp;[<A
 HREF="TrackRecord_feb08.html#self_vortex-antivortex_unpubl">2</A>] was conceived
and coordinated by myself, and carried out in collaboration with postdoctoral
peers in Dresden.  

<P>
<B><I>Concepts from quantum information (QI) for condensed matter</I></B>.
More recently, my research has focused on using calculations of
<B>entanglement entropy</B>, to study condensed matter issues.
One motivation is to explore a type of unconventional order known as
<B>topological order</B>.  For one class of topologically ordered states,
namely fractional quantum Hall (FQH) states, we calculated various possible
entanglement entropies [<A
 HREF="TrackRecord_feb08.html#our-prl07">7</A>,<A
 HREF="TrackRecord_feb08.html#our-pfaffian-entng">8</A>].  We demonstrated
that entanglement measures contain signatures of both topological order and of
the exotic ``exclusion statistics'' of FQH states.  Our work has shown that
entanglement measures provide a novel and useful probe for nontrivial
many-particle correlations. 

<P>
<B><I>Other systems</I></B>.
Outside the two themes above, I have addressed collective phenomena in several
other contexts, <I>e.g.</I>, 
<BR>
<UL>
<LI> Wigner crystals; 2D electrons on liquid helium [<A
 HREF="TrackRecord_feb08.html#self_WigCrys_PRB03">9</A>].

<LI> The uniform Bose gas; using quantum optics concepts to describe
   many-particle correlations [<A
   HREF="TrackRecord_feb08.html#self_squeez_PRA06">10</A>,<A
   HREF="TrackRecord_feb08.html#self_tc_cm02">11</A>,<A
   HREF="TrackRecord_feb08.html#self_tc-reveiew_cm03">12</A>].

<LI> Laser-induced dynamics in semiconductor quantum wells; pattern
formation via reaction-diffusion; electron-hole &amp; exciton dynamics
[<A HREF="TrackRecord_feb08.html#self_ring_PRB06">13</A>].

<LI> Pomeranchuk instabilities in correlated fermion systems [<A
HREF="TrackRecord_feb08.html#self_pomeranchuk_SCES07">15</A>,<A
HREF="TrackRecord_feb08.html#self_pomeranchuk_unpubl">14</A>].

</UL>

<BR>

<P>
<B><I>Current work (cold atoms)</I></B>. 
With postdoctoral collaborators in Dresden, I am studying the response of a
trapped BEC to sudden changes of interaction or trap.

<P>
<B><I>Current work (applying Q.I. concepts)</I></B>. 
(Several different collaborations.)  I am computing entanglement entropies in
unconventional 2D states: (1) so-called <I>chiral spin liquid</I> states, and
(2) several <I>quantum dimer model</I> states.  I am also performing
entanglement calculations with the aim of identifying phase transitions, in
(1) a frustrated one-dimensional spin model, and (2) FQH systems.

<P>
<B><I>Broadness and publication count</I></B>.  

Not confining myself to a narrow subfield has provided me with
wide-ranging skills and a mature perspective, which I believe is good
compensation for any penalty paid in publication count.  

<BR>I am now submitting four papers per year.

<P>
<B><I>Methods &amp; motivations</I></B>. 

The methods I used for my work have ranged widely across the theorists'
toolbox, from computer-based heavily numerical work [<A
 HREF="TrackRecord_feb08.html#our-pfaffian-entng">8</A>,<A
 HREF="TrackRecord_feb08.html#self_deformation_PRL07">5</A>,<A
 HREF="TrackRecord_feb08.html#self_ring_PRB06">13</A>,<A
 HREF="TrackRecord_feb08.html#self_sweep_PRA05">1</A>], through conceptual
argumentation [<A
 HREF="TrackRecord_feb08.html#self_polarized_PRA06">3</A>,<A
 HREF="TrackRecord_feb08.html#self_ring_PRB06">13</A>,<A
 HREF="TrackRecord_feb08.html#self_superstring_PRL05">6</A>,<A
 HREF="TrackRecord_feb08.html#self_WigCrys_PRB03">9</A>], all the way to purely analytical
and algebraic work [<A
 HREF="TrackRecord_feb08.html#self_squeez_PRA06">10</A>,<A
 HREF="TrackRecord_feb08.html#self_tc_cm02">11</A>,<A
 HREF="TrackRecord_feb08.html#self_pomeranchuk_unpubl">14</A>].  The motivations in my various projects have also
varied across the spectrum of condensed matter science, from explaining
particular experiments [<A
 HREF="TrackRecord_feb08.html#self_polarized_PRA06">3</A>,<A
 HREF="TrackRecord_feb08.html#self_Rice_PRL06">4</A>,<A
 HREF="TrackRecord_feb08.html#self_deformation_PRL07">5</A>,<A
 HREF="TrackRecord_feb08.html#self_sweep_PRA05">1</A>,<A
 HREF="TrackRecord_feb08.html#self_ring_PRB06">13</A>] to calculations
motivated by purely theoretical issues [<A
 HREF="TrackRecord_feb08.html#our-prl07">7</A>,<A
 HREF="TrackRecord_feb08.html#our-pfaffian-entng">8</A>,<A
 HREF="TrackRecord_feb08.html#self_squeez_PRA06">10</A>].

<BR>I expect my future work to be similarly broad, in terms of both techniques
and perspectives. 

